docs.abstract: Otto F. Warmbier, a student at the University of Virginia, died after suffering a severe brain injury during 17 months in custody in Pyongyang.
docs.snippet: Otto F. Warmbier, a student at the University of Virginia, died after suffering a severe brain injury during 17 months in custody in Pyongyang.
docs.lead_paragraph: WASHINGTON — The parents of Otto F. Warmbier, the Cincinnati college student who died after suffering a severe brain injury during 17 months in custody in Pyongyang, sued North Korea on Thursday, alleging that it kidnapped, tortured and murdered their son.

headline.main: Parents Sue North Korea Over College Student’s Death After Time in Prison
headline.print_headline: Parents Sue North Korea Over Student’s Death

docs.lead_paragraph: WASHINGTON — When the United States sought to punish Russia last month for its election interference and other aggressions, it targeted some of Russia’s wealthiest men, imposing sanctions on those viewed as enriching themselves off President Vladimir V. Putin’s government.

headline.main: Viktor Vekselberg, Russian Billionaire, Was Questioned by Mueller’s Investigators

docs.abstract: Lawmakers must approve the bill by midnight Friday to avoid a government shutdown this weekend, which would be the third closing this year.
docs.snippet: Lawmakers must approve the bill by midnight Friday to avoid a government shutdown this weekend, which would be the third closing this year.
docs.lead_paragraph: WASHINGTON — With government funding set to run out this weekend, congressional leaders agreed on a voluminous $1.3 trillion spending bill on Wednesday that would beef up domestic and military programs and keep the government open through September.

headline.main: Congressional Leaders Agree on $1.3 Trillion Spending Bill as Deadline Looms
headline.print_headline: Leaders in Congress Reach an Agreement To Spend $1.3 Trillion

docs.abstract: The president’s latest made-up statement renewed the question: When does he know the things he says are false and when is he simply misinformed?
docs.snippet: The president’s latest made-up statement renewed the question: When does he know the things he says are false and when is he simply misinformed?
docs.lead_paragraph: WASHINGTON — When President Trump told donors at a fund-raiser this past week that he had invented a fact during a conversation with Canada’s prime minister, the surprise was not that America’s leader makes things up, but that he openly admitted it.

headline.main: Trump and the Truth: A President Tests His Own Credibility
headline.print_headline: When Fiction  Is a Fact of Life

docs.abstract: If the Democrats win a special House race in Pennsylvania’s 18th District, the alarm bells will be audible across the country.
docs.snippet: If the Democrats win a special House race in Pennsylvania’s 18th District, the alarm bells will be audible across the country.
docs.lead_paragraph: PITTSBURGH — Never has so much money been spent so quickly on a political race with so little real meaning than on the House special election here, but to Republicans, the public relations debacle that would come with a loss this Tuesday is a price they cannot bear.

headline.main: Why G.O.P. Is Spending Millions on a Soon-to-Vanish Seat in Trump Country
